@Robert Reznik Well, I don't know when you had the grass-fed beef, but ranchers are now learning they need smaller animals and to fatten them up, not go for lean beef, which is tough and doesn't taste as good. But the best filet mignon I ever had was one I prepared myself from grass-fed beef a few months ago. It was tender and had much more flavor than one I had had in a restaurant that specialised in grain-finished beef a year ago, which was tender but had no flavor. 

Joel Salatin says he gets 4 cow days per acre compared to 1 cow day for his conventional neighbors, a cow day being how much feed a cow can eat in a day. So if your land provides 4 x as much food for your animals and zero cost other than providing water and perhaps some minerals, that's a great yield, especially given it has better nutrition and gives the animals a great life in a variety of settings with plenty of the food they love.

Most regenerative farmers have smaller animals, around 1,000 pounds, so they don't tear up their pastures when it rains. This is important if you don't want to have to spend a lot on hay. If you watch Greg Judy's videos, his South Poll cows look gorgeous and are calm and happily chewing away. He leaves enough grass before moving them once or twice a day so it can grow back in a couple of months and provide another feeding. This is a great system. It does take some thought and effort, but not as much as you'd think. I believe it could help a lot of the problems we have facing us today, including health issues, unemployment, pollution, global warming, and poor nutrition. And most of all, farmers struggling to make ends meet.

